  "text": "As listed in Table 2 , the initial degradation temperatures (Ti2) of the SPI films modified with MCC were higher than that of other films, indicating a presence of abundant hydrogen bond groups formed in the protein chains [CITATION_1] . Moreover, the SPI-MCC-Cu film had the highest degradation rate (Tmax2) at the highest temperature in the DTG curve compared with the control film, markedly increasing from 304.85 to 329.06 °C, which might be attributed to the cross-linking reactions among As listed in Table 2 , the initial degradation temperatures (T i2 ) of the SPI films modified with MCC were higher than that of other films, indicating a presence of abundant hydrogen bond groups formed in the protein chains [CITATION_2] . Moreover, the SPI-MCC-Cu film had the highest degradation rate (T max2 ) at the highest temperature in the DTG curve compared with the control film, markedly increasing from 304.85 to 329.06 • C, which might be attributed to the cross-linking reactions among MCC, NCs, and SPI. Therefore, we can conclude that the thermal stability of the SPI-NC films was improved by the modification of MCC. Table 2 . Thermo-degradation data of the untreated SPI films and the SPI films modified with Cu NCs, Zn NCs, and MCC. T i : initial temperature of degradation; T max : temperature at maximum degradation rate.",
